default0.    
defaultThe findings from the research projects I have conducted 
defaultreveal how the educational system works to positively affirm white 
defaultupper and 
defaultmiddle class identities, acting as a means of finding yourself as a successful ‘bright’ learner. In contrast, the ed
defaultucational system is rarely about positive affirmation for the working classes.  They are at far greater risk of losing rather than finding themselves, of both being unable to construct a successful learner identity and feeling  that their working class roo
defaultts and sense of self have no value in a context where working class culture and identity is constructed as a hindrance to academic achievement. The sense of shame and humiliation was palpable throughout the interviews I carried out with white working class
default pupils in London schools fo
defaultr an ESCR study on pupils’  perspectives on their teaching and learning
default: 
default&#xa0;
defaultDanny: Some teachers say, ‘That isn’t the way you talk’ – like
defaultputting you down. I think telling you a different way is
defaultsort of good, but I think the way
default they do it isn’t good
defaultbecause they make you look stupid.
defaultMartin: Those teachers look down on you
defaultDanny: Yeah, like they think you’re dumb … we don’t expect them
defaultto treat us like their own children. We’re not. But we are
defaultstill kids. I’d say to them, You’ve
default got kids. You treat them
defaultwith love but you don’t need to love us. All you need to
defaultdo is treat us like humans.
defaultThese commonplace feelings of  shame and humiliation often turned into a sense of futility and pointlessness in relation to academic learning: 
